# Luna AI/ML Platform - Architectural Instructions

## Overview

This document provides detailed architectural instructions for the Luna AI/ML platform on Google Cloud Platform (GCP). The architecture enables a tiered self-service experience for AI/ML workloads from experimentation through production deployment, with emphasis on UI application hosting via Kubernetes.

## High-Level Architecture Context

### Platform Positioning
- Luna operates as the primary AI/ML platform within the CDH (Cloud Data Hub) organizational folder in GCP
- Sits alongside but separate from DCP (Data and Cloud Platform) team's application hosting space
- Provides self-service ML workload deployment with governance and standardization
- Bridges the gap between data science experimentation and production ML application hosting

### Core Design Principles  
- Tiered user experience (Basic, Intermediate, Advanced, Exceptional)
- Template-driven deployment with opinionated defaults
- Minimal Kubernetes expertise required for end users
- GitOps-based deployment and promotion workflows
- Containerized workloads with standardized CI/CD pipelines

## Detailed Component Architecture

### 1. User Interface Layer

#### Luna Service Portal
- **Technology**: Web-based self-service portal
- **Authentication**: Integration with organizational SSO/OAuth providers
- **User Experience**: Tiered catalog interface presenting appropriate options based on user tier
- **Functionality**: Template selection, configuration input, deployment request submission, status monitoring

#### Service Catalog Integration
- **Technology**: GCP Service Catalog integration
- **Purpose**: Present standardized ML service offerings (notebooks, datasets, buckets, compute resources)
- **User Flow**: Quick-start resource provisioning for Basic tier users

### 2. Template and Configuration Management

#### Coppia Templating Engine  
- **Technology**: Python-based templating system (described as "terrible version of backstage")
- **Function**: Converts user inputs and selected templates into deployable configurations
- **Input**: User parameters, tier selection, workload type
- **Output**: Generated repository structure, Helm charts, Terraform configurations, CI/CD pipelines

#### Template Repository Structure
- **Basic Tier Templates**: Pre-configured notebooks, simple compute instances, data access patterns
- **Intermediate Tier Templates**: Opinionated ML pipeline frameworks, standardized Docker images, CI/CD patterns
- **Advanced Tier Templates**: Customizable infrastructure patterns, custom container support, advanced networking
- **UI Application Templates**: Streamlit applications, model serving endpoints, interactive dashboards

### 3. Source Code Management Layer

#### GitLab Instances (Multi-Environment)
- **Green Side Old**: Legacy GitLab instance
- **Green Side New**: Current production GitLab instance  
- **Red Side**: Arkham-specific GitLab instance (isolated from green side environments)
- **Repository Strategy**: Currently one repository per environment (noted as problematic architecture)
- **Access Control**: Environment-specific permissions and deployment gates

#### Repository Generation Flow
- User submits template request → Coppia processes inputs → New repository created from template → Initial commit with generated configurations → CI/CD pipeline triggered

### 4. Container and Artifact Management

#### GCP Artifact Registry
- **Purpose**: Centralized storage for Docker images, Helm charts, and other deployment artifacts
- **Organization**: Separate registries per environment and tier
- **Content**: Pre-built base images, user-generated application containers, Helm charts

#### Pre-built Image Strategy
- **Base Images**: Standardized Python, TensorFlow, PyTorch containers optimized for ML workloads
- **Intermediate Tier**: Opinionated images with common ML libraries and frameworks pre-installed
- **Advanced Tier**: Support for custom base images and containers
- **Security**: Automated vulnerability scanning and policy enforcement

### 5. CI/CD and Deployment Pipeline

#### GitLab CI/CD Pipelines
- **Trigger**: Git commits to template-generated repositories
- **Stages**: Code quality checks, container building, security scanning, artifact publishing
- **Integration**: Webhook-based triggering of downstream deployment processes

#### ArgoCD GitOps Implementation
- **Purpose**: Declarative deployment management for Kubernetes workloads
- **Architecture**: ArgoCD monitors Git repositories for configuration changes
- **Deployment Flow**: Git commit → ArgoCD detects change → Helm deployment to target GKE cluster
- **Environment Promotion**: Separate ArgoCD applications per environment with approval workflows

### 6. Container Orchestration Layer

#### Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) - Arkham Pattern
- **Cluster Architecture**: Multi-cluster setup with environment separation (dev, staging, production)
- **Arkham Pattern**: Hybrid cloud abstraction layer combining open-source tools with GCP services
- **Service Mesh**: Istio integration for traffic management, security, and observability
- **Ingress**: Google Cloud Load Balancer integration with automated TLS certificate management

#### Helm Chart Management
- **Chart Repository**: Centralized Helm chart storage in Artifact Registry
- **Template Structure**: Standardized charts for common ML workload patterns
- **Configuration**: Values files generated by Coppia templating system
- **Deployment**: ArgoCD-managed Helm releases with rollback capabilities

#### Kubernetes Resource Organization
- **Namespaces**: Tenant isolation with resource quotas and network policies
- **Service Accounts**: Workload identity integration with GCP IAM
- **Secrets Management**: Google Secret Manager integration
- **Storage**: Persistent volumes for stateful ML workloads, integration with Google Cloud Storage

### 7. Infrastructure as Code

#### Terraform Modules
- **Organization**: Reusable modules for common infrastructure patterns
- **Scope**: GKE clusters, networking, IAM roles, storage resources
- **State Management**: Remote state storage in Google Cloud Storage with locking
- **Integration**: Called from CI/CD pipelines for infrastructure provisioning

#### Infrastructure Deployment Flow
- Template generation includes Terraform configurations → CI/CD pipeline applies infrastructure changes → Kubernetes resources deployed on provisioned infrastructure

### 8. ML-Specific Services

#### Vertex AI Integration
- **Pipelines**: Integration with Vertex AI Pipelines for complex ML workflows
- **Training**: Scalable model training using Vertex AI Training service
- **Serving**: Model deployment via Vertex AI Prediction or custom serving infrastructure
- **Experiments**: Integration with Vertex AI Experiments for tracking and comparison

#### Model and Data Management
- **Model Registry**: Centralized storage and versioning of trained models
- **Data Sources**: Integration with Google Cloud Storage, BigQuery, and other data platforms
- **Feature Store**: Centralized feature management and serving
- **Monitoring**: Model performance and data drift detection capabilities

### 9. Future Extensibility

#### Gemini AI Integration (Planned)
- **Interface**: Chat-based interaction for deployment requests and configuration assistance
- **Templates**: AI-assisted template generation and parameter recommendation
- **Integration Point**: Within the service portal as an alternative input method

#### Weights & Biases Integration (Planned)
- **Experiment Tracking**: Automated integration with ML experiment tracking
- **Pipeline Integration**: Seamless logging from Vertex AI Pipelines to W&B
- **Reporting**: Centralized experiment results and model performance tracking

## User Journey Flows

### Basic Tier User Flow (Data Scientist)
1. User authenticates to Luna Service Portal
2. Selects Basic tier service from catalog (notebook, dataset access, compute)
3. Minimal configuration required (resource size, access permissions)
4. Coppia generates simple provisioning request
5. Direct GCP service provisioning via Service Catalog
6. User receives access credentials and service endpoints
7. Resources auto-expire based on policy settings

### Intermediate Tier User Flow (ML Engineer)
1. User authenticates to Luna Service Portal  
2. Selects intermediate template (ML pipeline, model serving, batch job)
3. Configures parameters (data sources, model artifacts, resource requirements)
4. Coppia generates complete repository structure with CI/CD pipeline
5. Repository created in appropriate GitLab instance
6. CI/CD pipeline triggered, building containers and infrastructure
7. ArgoCD deploys Helm charts to target GKE cluster
8. User receives deployment status and application endpoints
9. Ongoing monitoring and alerting automatically configured

### Advanced Tier User Flow (Expert ML Engineer)  
1. User authenticates to Luna Service Portal
2. Selects advanced template or starts from minimal base
3. Extensive configuration options (custom containers, infrastructure, networking)
4. Coppia generates customizable repository with advanced CI/CD patterns
5. User can modify generated Terraform, Helm charts, and Dockerfiles
6. Full GitOps workflow with manual approval gates for infrastructure changes
7. Custom deployment patterns supported alongside standard workflows

### UI Application Deployment Flow
1. User selects UI application template (Streamlit, custom web app, model serving interface)
2. Configures application parameters (model endpoints, UI frameworks, resource requirements)
3. Coppia generates application repository with Dockerfile, Kubernetes manifests, Helm chart
4. CI/CD pipeline builds container image and publishes to Artifact Registry
5. ArgoCD deploys application to GKE cluster with ingress configuration
6. Google Cloud Load Balancer provides external access with managed TLS certificates  
7. Application URL provided to user with operational dashboards and logging links

## Integration Points and Data Flow

### Template Processing Flow
Portal Request → Authentication → Template Selection → Coppia Processing → Repository Generation → CI/CD Trigger → Container Build → Artifact Storage → ArgoCD Sync → Helm Deployment → Kubernetes Pods → Load Balancer → User Access

### Monitoring and Observability Flow
Kubernetes Metrics → Google Cloud Monitoring → Custom Dashboards → Alerting → Notification Channels → User/Operator Response

### Environment Promotion Flow  
Development GitLab → CI/CD Testing → Staging GitLab → Approval Process → Production GitLab → ArgoCD Production Sync → Production Kubernetes Deployment

### Model Lifecycle Flow
Data Sources → Vertex AI Training → Model Registry → Model Validation → Deployment Templates → Container Packaging → Kubernetes Serving → Performance Monitoring → Drift Detection → Retraining Trigger

## Security and Compliance Architecture

### Identity and Access Management
- GCP IAM integration with organizational identity provider
- Service account-based workload identity for Kubernetes pods
- Least privilege access patterns enforced at template level
- Audit logging for all platform interactions and deployments

### Network Security
- VPC-native GKE clusters with private node pools
- Network policies for namespace isolation
- Istio service mesh for encrypted inter-service communication
- Private Google Access for GCP service integration

### Compliance and Governance  
- Policy-as-code enforcement at deployment time
- Automated security scanning for containers and infrastructure
- Audit trails for all deployments and configuration changes
- Data residence and sovereignty controls where required

